{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"375deb4f-f49c-446b-a2e3-0c1664f41f7a","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is passed to the new platform runner. You'll also need these NuGet packages in each test project:\n\n| VSTest feature | Package to add |\n|---|---|\n| TRX logger | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| Code coverage | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\nAnd enable the new platform in each test `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>   <!-- or UseVSTest=false for xUnit/NUnit -->\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key differences:** `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`, `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` → `--coverage`, `--blame-*` → `--crashdump` / `--hangdump`, and all platform flags go after the `--` separator.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38bf4328-f8a2-40b8-8994-517e31444a61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a `dotnet test` command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling, not a codebase task. Let me provide the answer based on my knowledge.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n1. **Filter**: `--filter` becomes `--filter` still works, but the CLI flag syntax changes. In Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you use `--filter` the same way actually, but when running via `dotnet test` it should still work. However, if running the test executable directly, it's `--filter`.\n\n\n2. **Logger**: The `--logger trx` flag changes to `--report-trx`, which is built-in once you add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package.\n3. **Code Coverage**: Code coverage collection shifts from the `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` syntax to using the `Microsoft.CodeCoverage` package with `--collect code-coverage`, though the `dotnet test --collect` command still functions for data collectors.\n4. **Blame**: Crash and hang detection flags become `--crashdump` and `--hang` respectively.\n\nComparing the two approaches—using `dotnet test` as a wrapper versus running the test app directly—reveals that while `dotnet test` translates some options, many change significantly. When running the test executable directly, filters like `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` remain the same, but reporting and diagnostics require the new flag names and their corresponding packages like `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` and `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashD`...\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how this works with `dotnet test` and Microsoft.Testing.Platform—the command-line interface shifts when using the new testing framework, and options are passed differently depending on whether you're using the `--` separator or the newer `dotnet test` experience in .NET 9+. Completing the command syntax...","outputTokens":1398,"requestId":"0837:1E21:6B9F32F:77FCFFA:69EABEC3"},"id":"adfb467b-6234-49be-9e9d-b4e8c5787495","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:52:46.100Z","parentId":"5d35a4ad-fa0e-4784-a4c9-836d79566c01"}
